  "text": "The inhibition of motility and flow that we observed with exenatide is likely to have reduced the length of small intestinal mucosa exposed to glucose [CITATION_1] , which is supported by our scintigraphic data, and to have diminished the thinning of the unstirred water layer, which occurs with flow of chyme [CITATION_2] ; both phenomena would contribute to reduced absorption of glucose, indicated by lower 3-OMG concentrations, despite a possible increase in mesenteric blood flow that occurs with GLP-1 receptor stimulation [CITATION_3] . That GLP-1 receptor agonists are associated with diarrhea in some patients may seem at odds with our observations but could be due to acceleration of colonic transit, which was observed independently of any effect on small intestinal motility with the GLP-1 receptor agonist ROSE-010 (21).",
